     1→# Claude Code WebSocket SDK Protocol — Reverse Engineered
     2→
     3→> **Reverse-engineered from Claude Code CLI v2.1.37 (`cli.js`) and Agent SDK v0.2.37 (`sdk.mjs`, `sdk.d.ts`)**
     4→>
     5→> This document describes the undocumented WebSocket protocol that Claude Code CLI uses for programmatic control via the `--sdk-url` flag. This is the same NDJSON protocol used over stdin/stdout, but transported over WebSocket — enabling full bidirectional control without tmux or PTY hacks.
     6→
     7→---
     8→
     9→## Table of Contents
    10→
    11→1. [Overview](#1-overview)
    12→2. [Launching Claude Code in WebSocket Mode](#2-launching-claude-code-in-websocket-mode)
    13→3. [Transport Architecture](#3-transport-architecture)
    14→4. [Connection Lifecycle](#4-connection-lifecycle)
    15→5. [Wire Protocol (NDJSON)](#5-wire-protocol-ndjson)
    16→6. [Message Types — Complete Reference](#6-message-types--complete-reference)
    17→7. [Control Protocol (13 Subtypes)](#7-control-protocol-13-subtypes)
    18→8. [Permission / Tool Approval Flow](#8-permission--tool-approval-flow)
    19→9. [Session Management](#9-session-management)
    20→10. [Reconnection & Resilience](#10-reconnection--resilience)
    21→11. [Environment Variables](#11-environment-variables)
    22→12. [Transport Class Hierarchy](#12-transport-class-hierarchy)
    23→13. [Implementation Guide](#13-implementation-guide)
    24→
    25→---
    26→
    27→## 1. Overview
    28→
    29→Claude Code CLI has a **hidden** `--sdk-url <ws-url>` flag (`.hideHelp()` in Commander) that makes the CLI act as a **WebSocket client**, connecting to a server you control. The protocol is **NDJSON** (newline-delimited JSON) — the same format used over stdin/stdout by the official `@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`.
    30→
    31→### Why This Matters
    32→
    33→- **No SDK dependency**: The `--sdk-url` flag is baked into the CLI binary itself
    34→- **Uses your Claude Code subscription**: No API billing, uses your existing plan
    35→- **Full programmatic control**: Send prompts, approve/deny permissions, interrupt execution
    36→- **Replaces tmux hacks**: Clean WebSocket channel instead of PTY automation
    37→- **Same protocol as Claude Code Web**: The web UI uses the same NDJSON-over-WebSocket approach
    38→
    39→### Key Characteristics
    40→
    41→| Property | Value |
    42→|----------|-------|
    43→| Transport | WebSocket (`ws://` or `wss://`) |
    44→| Protocol | NDJSON (one JSON object per `\n`-terminated line) |
    45→| Direction | CLI connects TO your server (CLI = client) |
    46→| Auth | `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header on upgrade |
    47→| First message | Server sends `user` message, CLI responds with `system/init` |
    48→| Keepalive | `keep_alive` messages + WebSocket ping/pong every 10s |
    49→
    50→---
    51→
    52→## 2. Launching Claude Code in WebSocket Mode
    53→
    54→### Basic Command
    55→
    56→```bash
    57→claude --sdk-url ws://localhost:8765 \
    58→       --print \
    59→       --output-format stream-json \
    60→       --input-format stream-json \
    61→       --verbose \
    62→       -p "placeholder"
    63→```
    64→
    65→### Required Flags
    66→
    67→| Flag | Required | Purpose |
    68→|------|----------|---------|
    69→| `--sdk-url <url>` | Yes | WebSocket URL to connect to |
    70→| `--print` (`-p`) | Yes | Enables headless/non-interactive mode |
    71→| `--output-format stream-json` | Yes | NDJSON output (validated by CLI) |
    72→| `--input-format stream-json` | Yes | NDJSON input (validated by CLI) |
    73→
    74→### Useful Optional Flags
    75→
    76→| Flag | Purpose |
    77→|------|---------|
    78→| `--verbose` | Include `stream_event` messages (token-by-token streaming) |
    79→| `--model <model>` | Override model (e.g., `claude-opus-4-6`) |
    80→| `--permission-mode <mode>` | Set initial permission mode |
    81→| `--allowedTools <tools>` | Auto-approve specific tools |
    82→| `--resume <session-id>` | Resume a previous session |
    83→| `--continue` | Continue the most recent session |
    84→| `--max-turns <n>` | Limit conversation turns |
    85→
    86→### Notes
    87→
    88→- The `-p "placeholder"` prompt argument is **ignored** when `--sdk-url` is used — the CLI waits for a `user` message over WebSocket instead
    89→- Both `--input-format` and `--output-format` must be `stream-json` (CLI exits with error otherwise)
    90→- The CLI will wait indefinitely for the first `user` message after connecting
    91→
    92→---
    93→
    94→## 3. Transport Architecture
    95→
    96→Six transport classes were deobfuscated from the minified CLI:
    97→
    98→```
    99→                           ┌─────────────────────┐
   100→                           │  ad1 (ProcessInput)  │  Base: NDJSON parser + control request/response
   101→                           │  - read() generator  │
   102→                           │  - sendRequest()     │
   103→                           │  - createCanUseTool() │
   104→                           └──────────┬──────────┘
   105→                                      │ extends
   106→                           ┌──────────▼──────────┐
   107→                           │  LQA (SdkUrl)        │  --sdk-url mode  ← OUR TARGET
   108→                           │  - PassThrough bridge │
   109→                           │  - transport delegate │
   110→                           └──────────┬──────────┘
   111→                                      │ uses
   112→                    ┌─────────────────┼─────────────────┐
   113→                    │                                     │
   114→          ┌─────────▼─────────┐              ┌───────────▼───────────┐
   115→          │  sd1 (WebSocket)   │              │  kQA (Hybrid)          │
   116→          │  - WS send+receive │              │  extends sd1           │
   117→          │  - reconnect logic │              │  - WS receive only     │
   118→          │  - message buffer  │              │  - HTTP POST for send  │
   119→          │  - ping/pong       │              │  - retry with backoff  │
   120→          └────────────────────┘              └────────────────────────┘
   121→
   122→  Web UI / Remote Sessions:
   123→          ┌────────────────────┐         ┌─────────────────────────┐
   124→          │  MFA (SessionsWS)  │◄────────│  WFA (RemoteSessionMgr) │
   125→          │  - Subscribe WS    │         │  - Permission routing   │
   126→          │  - API auth        │         │  - HTTP POST for send   │
   127→          └────────────────────┘         └─────────────────────────┘
   128→
   129→  Direct Connect (Browser):
   130→          ┌────────────────────┐
   131→          │  fFA (DirectConnect)│  Simplified WS for browser use
   132→          │  - sendMessage()   │
   133→          │  - respondToPermit │
   134→          │  - sendInterrupt() │
   135→          └────────────────────┘
   136→```
   137→
   138→### Transport Selection Logic
   139→
   140→```typescript
   141→function createTransport(url: URL, headers?: Record<string, string>, sessionId?: string) {
   142→  if (url.protocol === "ws:" || url.protocol === "wss:") {
   143→    if (process.env.CLAUDE_CODE_POST_FOR_SESSION_INGRESS_V2) {
   144→      return new HybridTransport(url, headers, sessionId);  // WS receive + HTTP POST send
   145→    }
   146→    return new WebSocketTransport(url, headers, sessionId);  // Pure WebSocket
   147→  }
   148→  throw Error(`Unsupported protocol: ${url.protocol}`);
   149→}
   150→```
   151→
   152→---
   153→
   154→## 4. Connection Lifecycle
   155→
   156→### Sequence Diagram
   157→
   158→```
   159→  Your Server (WS)                          Claude Code CLI
   160→       │                                         │
   161→       │◄──────── WebSocket CONNECT ──────────────│  (with Auth header)
   162→       │                                         │
   163→       │                                         │──► system/init message
   164→       │◄──────── {"type":"system","subtype":"init",...} ──│
   165→       │                                         │
   166→       │──── {"type":"user","message":{...}} ────►│  (you send first prompt)
   167→       │                                         │
   168→       │                                         │──► LLM processing...
   169→       │                                         │
   170→       │◄──── {"type":"stream_event",...} ────────│  (if --verbose)
   171→       │◄──── {"type":"stream_event",...} ────────│
   172→       │◄──── {"type":"assistant",...} ───────────│  (full response)
   173→       │                                         │
   174→       │  (if tool needs permission)              │
   175→       │◄──── {"type":"control_request",          │
   176→       │       "request":{"subtype":"can_use_tool"│
   177→       │       ,"tool_name":"Bash",...}} ─────────│
   178→       │                                         │
   179→       │──── {"type":"control_response",          │  (you approve/deny)
   180→       │      "response":{"subtype":"success",    │
   181→       │      "request_id":"...","response":      │
   182→       │      {"behavior":"allow",...}}} ─────────►│
   183→       │                                         │
   184→       │◄──── {"type":"assistant",...} ───────────│  (continues after approval)
   185→       │◄──── {"type":"result",...} ──────────────│  (query complete)
   186→       │                                         │
   187→       │──── {"type":"user","message":{...}} ────►│  (next turn, optional)
   188→       │         ...                              │
   189→```
   190→
   191→### Authentication
   192→
   193→The CLI sends authentication via HTTP headers on the WebSocket upgrade request:
   194→
   195→```
   196→Authorization: Bearer <session_access_token>
   197→X-Environment-Runner-Version: <version>  (optional)
   198→X-Last-Request-Id: <uuid>  (on reconnect, for message replay)
   199→```
   200→
   201→**Token sources** (priority order):
   202→1. `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ACCESS_TOKEN` environment variable
   203→2. Internal session ingress token
   204→3. Token read from file descriptor specified by `CLAUDE_CODE_WEBSOCKET_AUTH_FILE_DESCRIPTOR`
   205→
   206→---
   207→
   208→## 5. Wire Protocol (NDJSON)
   209→
   210→Each message is a single JSON object followed by `\n` (newline). Multiple messages can be sent in sequence.
   211→
   212→```
   213→{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Hello"},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":""}\n
   214→{"type":"assistant","message":{...},"session_id":"abc123","uuid":"..."}\n
   215→```
   216→
   217→### Message Categories
   218→
   219→| Direction | Types |
   220→|-----------|-------|
   221→| **Server → CLI** | `user`, `control_response`, `control_cancel_request`, `keep_alive`, `update_environment_variables` |
   222→| **CLI → Server** | `system`, `assistant`, `result`, `stream_event`, `tool_progress`, `tool_use_summary`, `auth_status`, `control_request` (can_use_tool, hook_callback), `keep_alive`, `streamlined_text`, `streamlined_tool_use_summary` |
   223→| **Bidirectional** | `control_request`, `control_response`, `keep_alive` |
   224→
   225→### Filtered by SDK (present on wire but not exposed to consumers)
   226→
   227→These types are present in the NDJSON stream but the official SDK filters them out:
   228→- `control_request` / `control_response` / `control_cancel_request` — handled internally
   229→- `keep_alive` — silently consumed
   230→- `streamlined_text` / `streamlined_tool_use_summary` — internal streamlined mode
   231→
   232→---
   233→
   234→## 6. Message Types — Complete Reference
   235→
   236→### 6.1. `user` — User Message (Server → CLI)
   237→
   238→Send a prompt or follow-up message to the Claude Code agent.
   239→
   240→```typescript
   241→interface SDKUserMessage {
   242→  type: "user";
   243→  message: {
   244→    role: "user";
   245→    content: string | ContentBlock[];  // string for simple text, array for structured
   246→  };
   247→  parent_tool_use_id: string | null;   // null for top-level, string for sub-agent
   248→  session_id: string;                  // "" for first message, then use session_id from init
   249→  uuid?: string;                       // optional
   250→  isSynthetic?: boolean;               // true for internally-generated messages
   251→}
   252→```
   253→
   254→**Example — Simple text prompt:**
   255→```json
   256→{
   257→  "type": "user",
   258→  "message": { "role": "user", "content": "What files are in this project?" },
   259→  "parent_tool_use_id": null,
   260→  "session_id": ""
   261→}
   262→```
   263→
   264→### 6.2. `system/init` — Initialization (CLI → Server)
   265→
   266→First message sent by the CLI after WebSocket connection. Contains full capability info.
   267→
   268→```typescript
   269→interface SDKSystemMessage {
   270→  type: "system";
   271→  subtype: "init";
   272→  cwd: string;
   273→  session_id: string;
   274→  tools: string[];                     // ["Task", "Bash", "Glob", "Grep", "Read", "Edit", "Write", ...]
   275→  mcp_servers: { name: string; status: string }[];
   276→  model: string;                       // "claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929"
   277→  permissionMode: PermissionMode;
   278→  apiKeySource: string;
   279→  claude_code_version: string;         // "2.1.37"
   280→  slash_commands: string[];
   281→  agents?: string[];
   282→  skills?: string[];
   283→  plugins?: { name: string; path: string }[];
   284→  output_style: string;
   285→  uuid: string;
   286→  session_id: string;
   287→}
   288→```
   289→
   290→### 6.3. `assistant` — LLM Response (CLI → Server)
   291→
   292→Full assistant message after LLM completes a response.
   293→
   294→```typescript
   295→interface SDKAssistantMessage {
   296→  type: "assistant";
   297→  message: {
   298→    id: string;                        // "msg_01..."
   299→    type: "message";
   300→    role: "assistant";
   301→    model: string;
   302→    content: ContentBlock[];           // text blocks, tool_use blocks, thinking blocks
   303→    stop_reason: string | null;        // "end_turn", "tool_use", etc.
   304→    usage: {
   305→      input_tokens: number;
   306→      output_tokens: number;
   307→      cache_creation_input_tokens: number;
   308→      cache_read_input_tokens: number;
   309→    };
   310→  };
   311→  parent_tool_use_id: string | null;
   312→  error?: "authentication_failed" | "billing_error" | "rate_limit" | "invalid_request" | "server_error" | "unknown";
   313→  uuid: string;
   314→  session_id: string;
   315→}
   316→```
   317→
   318→### 6.4. `stream_event` — Streaming Chunks (CLI → Server)
   319→
   320→Token-by-token streaming events. Only sent when `--verbose` flag is used.
   321→
   322→```typescript
   323→interface SDKPartialAssistantMessage {
   324→  type: "stream_event";
   325→  event: BetaRawMessageStreamEvent;    // Anthropic streaming event
   326→  parent_tool_use_id: string | null;
   327→  uuid: string;
   328→  session_id: string;
   329→}
   330→```
   331→
   332→### 6.5. `result` — Query Complete (CLI → Server)
   333→
   334→Sent when the query finishes (success or error).
   335→
   336→```typescript
   337→// Success
   338→interface SDKResultSuccess {
   339→  type: "result";
   340→  subtype: "success";
   341→  is_error: false;
   342→  result: string;                      // final text result
   343→  duration_ms: number;
   344→  duration_api_ms: number;
   345→  num_turns: number;
   346→  total_cost_usd: number;
   347→  stop_reason: string | null;
   348→  usage: {
   349→    input_tokens: number;
   350→    output_tokens: number;
   351→    cache_creation_input_tokens: number;
   352→    cache_read_input_tokens: number;
   353→  };
   354→  modelUsage: Record<string, {
   355→    inputTokens: number;
   356→    outputTokens: number;
   357→    cacheReadInputTokens: number;
   358→    cacheCreationInputTokens: number;
   359→    webSearchRequests: number;
   360→    costUSD: number;
   361→    contextWindow: number;
   362→    maxOutputTokens: number;
   363→  }>;
   364→  permission_denials: { tool_name: string; tool_use_id: string; tool_input: Record<string, unknown> }[];
   365→  structured_output?: unknown;
   366→  uuid: string;
   367→  session_id: string;
   368→}
   369→
   370→// Error
   371→interface SDKResultError {
   372→  type: "result";
   373→  subtype: "error_during_execution" | "error_max_turns" | "error_max_budget_usd" | "error_max_structured_output_retries";
   374→  is_error: true;
   375→  errors: string[];
   376→  duration_ms: number;
   377→  duration_api_ms: number;
   378→  num_turns: number;
   379→  total_cost_usd: number;
   380→  stop_reason: string | null;
   381→  usage: NonNullableUsage;
   382→  modelUsage: Record<string, ModelUsage>;
   383→  permission_denials: SDKPermissionDenial[];
   384→  uuid: string;
   385→  session_id: string;
   386→}
   387→```
   388→
   389→### 6.6. `system/status` — Status Change (CLI → Server)
   390→
   391→```typescript
   392→interface SDKStatusMessage {
   393→  type: "system";
   394→  subtype: "status";
   395→  status: "compacting" | null;         // null = compacting ended
   396→  permissionMode?: PermissionMode;     // included when mode changes
   397→  uuid: string;
   398→  session_id: string;
   399→}
   400→```
   401→
   402→### 6.7. `system/compact_boundary` — Post-Compaction (CLI → Server)
   403→
   404→```typescript
   405→interface SDKCompactBoundaryMessage {
   406→  type: "system";
   407→  subtype: "compact_boundary";
   408→  compact_metadata: {
   409→    trigger: "manual" | "auto";
   410→    pre_tokens: number;
   411→  };
   412→  uuid: string;
   413→  session_id: string;
   414→}
   415→```
   416→
   417→### 6.8. `tool_progress` — Tool Execution Heartbeat (CLI → Server)
   418→
   419→```typescript
   420→interface SDKToolProgressMessage {
   421→  type: "tool_progress";
   422→  tool_use_id: string;
   423→  tool_name: string;
   424→  parent_tool_use_id: string | null;
   425→  elapsed_time_seconds: number;
   426→  uuid: string;
   427→  session_id: string;
   428→}
   429→```
   430→
   431→### 6.9. `tool_use_summary` — Tool Execution Summary (CLI → Server)
   432→
   433→```typescript
   434→interface SDKToolUseSummaryMessage {
   435→  type: "tool_use_summary";
   436→  summary: string;
   437→  preceding_tool_use_ids: string[];
   438→  uuid: string;
   439→  session_id: string;
   440→}
   441→```
   442→
   443→### 6.10. `auth_status` — Authentication Flow (CLI → Server)
   444→
   445→```typescript
   446→interface SDKAuthStatusMessage {
   447→  type: "auth_status";
   448→  isAuthenticating: boolean;
   449→  output: string[];
   450→  error?: string;
   451→  uuid: string;
   452→  session_id: string;
   453→}
   454→```
   455→
   456→### 6.11. `system/task_notification` — Sub-Agent Task Done (CLI → Server)
   457→
   458→```typescript
   459→interface SDKTaskNotificationMessage {
   460→  type: "system";
   461→  subtype: "task_notification";
   462→  task_id: string;
   463→  status: "completed" | "failed" | "stopped";
   464→  output_file: string;
